\n| 14 || December 7, 2008 || '''Denver Broncos''' || '''L''' 17\u201324 || 3:05&nbsp;PM CST || [[INVESCO Field at Mile High]] || CBS || 2\u201311 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20081218055256/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29730&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG14 Recap]\n|-  style=\"background:#fdd; text-align:center;\"\n| 15 || December 14, 2008 || '''San Diego Chargers''' || '''L''' 21\u201322 || 12:00&nbsp;PM CST || Arrowhead Stadium || CBS || 2\u201312 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20090109055902/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29744&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG15%20Recap Recap]\n|-  style=\"background:#fdd; text-align:center;\"\n| 16 || December 21, 2008 || Miami Dolphins || '''L''' 31\u201338 || 12:00&nbsp;PM CST || Arrowhead Stadium || CBS || 2\u201313 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20081222140234/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29756&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG16 Recap]\n|-  style=\"background:#fdd; text-align:center;\"\n| 17 || December 28, 2008 || [[2008 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] || '''L''' 6\u201316 || 12:00&nbsp;PM CST || [[Paul Brown Stadium]] || CBS || 2\u201314 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20081231130224/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29771&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG17&override=true Recap]\n|}\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Week 1: at New England Patriots===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Patriots'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 3 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 7\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 3\n|date= September 7, 2008\n| Location = [[Gillette Stadium]], [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 2:49\n| Attendance = 68,756\n| Weather = Sunny skies; 75&nbsp;\u00b0F (23.9&nbsp;\u00b0C); Wind NW at 15&nbsp;mph\n| Referee = [[Carl Cheffers]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| FirstEntry = yes\n| Quarter = Q2 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 11:45 | Team = NE | Event = [[Randy Moss]] 10&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Matt Cassel]] ([[Stephen Gostkowski]] kick) | Score = NE 7\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:17 | Team = KC | Event = [[Nick Novak]] 40&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = NE 7\u20133\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q3 | QuarterEntries = 1\n| Time = 03:01 | Team = NE | Event = [[Sammy Morris]] 5&nbsp;yd TD run (Gostkowski kick) | Score = NE 14\u20133\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q4 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 13:06 | Team = KC | Event = [[Dwayne Bowe]] 13&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Damon Huard]] (Novak kick) | Score = NE 14\u201310\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 02:26 | Team = NE | Event = Gostkowski 37&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = NE 17\u201310\n| LastEntry = yes\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Chiefs played the defending AFC Champion New England Patriots, and were 16 \u00bd-point underdogs entering the game. With 7:20 left in the first quarter, [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] [[Bernard Pollard]] hit [[quarterback]] [[Tom Brady]] in his left leg.<ref name=\"Brady\">Associated Press. [http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa5bd5&template=with-video&confirm=true Chiefs safety Pollard regrets Brady's injury] ''NFL.com'', September 8, 2008.</ref> Brady went down, clutching his left knee and would not return to play in the game. Back\u2013up quarterback [[Matt Cassel]] entered the game, and his first pass of the game went 51&nbsp;yards to [[wide receiver]] [[Randy Moss]]. Cassel continued to excel as he was 5\u20136 on the drive. It ended on a 10-yard touchdown pass to Moss, giving the heavily favored Patriots the early lead in the second quarter. Five drives later the Chiefs got on the scoreboard after a 13-play drive that ended on a 40-yard field goal from [[Place kicker|kicker]] [[Nick Novak]]. However, New England replied with their second touchdown of the day, this time a 5-yard run by [[running back]] [[Sammy Morris]]. Chiefs quarterback [[Brodie Croyle]] was hurt when he was sacked and slammed to the turf on his shoulder.<ref name=\"Croyle out\">Associated Press. [http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true Chiefs QB Croyle out for this week] ''NFL.com'', September 8, 2008.</ref> With around 50&nbsp;seconds on the clock and down by a touchdown in the fourth quarter, the Chiefs had the ball near the Patriots goal line. Kansas City had a chance to score but Dwayne Bowe dropped a pass in the end zone on fourth down, leading the Patriots victory. The loss also gave them a franchise-worst 10-straight losses, dating back to last season.e tried to throw on the sideline, but immediately indicated he was through for the day.<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/> [[Damon Huard]] substituted for Croyle and had the Chiefs on the 5-yard line when they ran out of downs. The Patriots won the game 17\u201310, and the Chiefs fell to an 0\u20131 start.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Week 2: vs. Oakland Raiders===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Raiders'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 6 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 10\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 0 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 8\n|date= September 14, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance = 74,480\n| Weather = 61&nbsp;\u00b0F (Cloudy)\n| Referee = [[Walt Anderson (American football official)|Walt Anderson]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Kevin Harlan]] & [[Rich Gannon]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| FirstEntry = yes\n| Quarter = Q1 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 05:13 | Team = OAK | Event = [[Sebastian Janikowski]] 56&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = OAK 3\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 01:19 | Team = OAK | Event = Janikowski 25&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = OAK 6\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q3 | QuarterEntries = 1\n| Time = 08:22 | Team = OAK | Event = [[Darren McFadden]] 19&nbsp;yd TD run (Janikowski kick) | Score = OAK 13\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q4 | QuarterEntries = 3\n| Time = 06:53 | Team = OAK | Event = Janikowski 40&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = OAK 16\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 04:04 | Team = KC | Event = [[Tony Gonzalez]] 2&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Tyler Thigpen]] (Thigpen pass to [[Mike Cox (fullback)|Mike Cox]] for 2-point conversion) | Score = OAK 16\u20138\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:51 | Team = OAK | Event = [[Michael Bush]] 32&nbsp;yd TD run (Janikowski kick) | Score = OAK 23\u20138\n| LastEntry = yes\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to rebound from their tough road loss to the Patriots, the Chiefs hosted their AFC West rival, the [[Oakland Raiders]].  In the first quarter, Kansas City trailed early as Raiders kicker [[Sebastian Janikowski]] got a 56-yard and a 25-yard field goal. Chiefs quarterback Damon Huard suffered a neck injury in the first quarter and [[Tyler Thigpen]] substituted as quarterback for the remainder of the game.<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\">Associated Press. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3587431 Chiefs' Huard replaced by Thigpen after injury] ''ESPN.com'', September 14, 2008.</ref> Huard was in for Kansas City's first two series, but didn't return after throwing an interception late in the second quarter.<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\"/> [[Marques Hagans]], who was listed on the Chiefs' roster as a wide receiver, checked in as quarterback for several draw plays.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> The Chiefs announced at the end of the third quarter that Huard sustained \"mild head trauma,\"<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> a move deemed controversial as Huard never sought medical attention in the following days.<ref name=\"Conspiracy\">Horing, Ari. [http://bleacherreport.com/articles/58610-do-the-chiefs-have-a-conspiracy-looming-in-kansas-city Do the Chiefs have a conspiracy looming in Kansas City?] ''Bleacher Report'', September 17, 2008.</ref>\n\nUnder Thigpen, the Chiefs' offense struggled to move the ball down the field. In using three quarterbacks, the Chiefs had only 65 net yards at halftime.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> Raiders RB [[Darren McFadden]] got a 19-yard TD run in the third quarter. Oakland increased its lead with Janikowski nailing a 40-yard field goal in the fourth quarter. The Chiefs would respond with rookie QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] completing a 2-yard TD pass to TE [[Tony Gonzalez]], Kansas City executed a [[two-point conversion]] pass to rookie FB [[Mike Cox (fullback)|Mike Cox]] to make them within 8 points with just over five minutes remaining.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> The Chiefs' two-point conversion was the team's first in two years.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> Kansas City lost its opportunity to tie the game as the Raiders pulled away with RB [[Michael Bush]] getting a 32-yard TD run.\n\nThe Chiefs' defense allowed the third-highest total yards on offense in franchise history.<ref name=\"Despite firing\">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=280914012 Despite firing reports, Kiffin, McFadden lead Raiders over Chiefs] ''ESPN.com'', September 14, 2008.</ref> [[JaMarcus Russell]] completed only 6 of 17 passes for 55&nbsp;yards and led the Raiders to a 15-point victory.<ref name=\"Chiefs hit rock bottom\">West, Joe. [http://nwanews.com/nwat/Sports/69190/ Chiefs hit rock bottom at Arrowhead] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919040752/http://nwanews.com/nwat/Sports/69190/ |date=September 19, 2008 }} ''Northwest Arkansas Times'', September 14, 2008.</ref> Following the game, Chiefs RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] voiced his displeasure with the Chiefs' offense and his role with the team.<ref name=\"Johnson unhappy\">Associated Press. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3587787 Chiefs RB Johnson unhappy with reduced role in offense] ''ESPN.com'', September 14, 2008.</ref> With the loss, the Chiefs fell to an 0\u20132 record for the third consecutive year.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/> Kansas City's 11-game losing streak (2007\u20132008) is the longest in franchise history.<ref name=\"Despite firing\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs hit rock bottom\"/> The Chiefs also lost their second consecutive game to the Raiders for the first time since 2001.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Week 3: at Atlanta Falcons===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Falcons'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 0\n| H1 = 14 | H2 = 10 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 7\n|date= September 21, 2008\n| Location = [[Georgia Dome]], [[Atlanta]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance = 62,434\n| Weather = Domed stadium\n| Referee = [[Scott Green (American football official)|Scott Green]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]] & [[Steve Tasker]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| FirstEntry = yes\n| Quarter = Q1 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 03:20 | Team = ATL | Event = [[Michael Turner (American football)|Michael Turner]] 4&nbsp;yd TD run ([[Jason Elam]] kick) | Score = ATL 7\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:07 | Team = ATL | Event = [[Roddy White]] 70&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] (Elam kick) | Score = ATL 14\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q2 | QuarterEntries = 3\n| Time = 09:15 | Team = ATL | Event = Elam 27&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = ATL 17\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 02:11 | Team = ATL | Event = Turner 1&nbsp;yd TD run (Elam kick) | Score = ATL 24\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:03 | Team = KC | Event = [[Dwayne Bowe]] 15&nbsp;yd TD pass from Thigpen ([[Nick Novak]] kick) | Score = ATL 24\u20137\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q3 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 09:49 | Team = KC | Event = [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] 1&nbsp;yd TD run (Novak kick) | Score = ATL 24\u201314\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 05:13 | Team = ATL | Event = Turner 2&nbsp;yd run (Elam kick) | Score = ATL 31\u201314\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q4 | QuarterEntries = 1\n| Time = 01:01 | Team = ATL | Event = [[Chris Houston (American football)|Chris Houston]] 10&nbsp;yd INT return (Elam kick) | Score = ATL 38\u201314\n| LastEntry = yes\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nTrying to snap a two-game losing skid, the Chiefs played a Week 3 interconference duel against the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. With [[Damon Huard]] still recovering, second-year quarterback [[Tyler Thigpen]] was given the start.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\">{{cite news | title=Chiefs QB Thigpen to start vs. Falcons | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861 | date=September 17, 2008 | accessdate=September 17, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919151055/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861| archivedate= September 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn the first quarter, Kansas City's struggled as Falcons RB [[Michael Turner (American football)|Michael Turner]] got a 4-yard TD run, along with QB [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] completing a 70-yard TD pass to WR [[Roddy White]].<ref name=\"Falcons back\">{{cite news | title=Falcons back on track after victory over winless Chiefs | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29560&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG3 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=NFL | date=September 21, 2008 | accessdate=November 27, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161602/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29560&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG3 | archivedate=December 11, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the second quarter, Atlanta increased its lead with kicker [[Jason Elam]] getting a 27-yard field goal, along with Turner's 1-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Falcons back\"/> The Chiefs would close out the first half with Thigpen completing a 15-yard TD pass to WR [[Dwayne Bowe]].<ref name=\"Falcons back\"/>\n\nIn the third quarter, Kansas City closed in on Atlanta's lead as RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] got a 1-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Falcons back\"/> However, the Falcons replied with Turner's 2-yard TD run, and a fourth quarter interception sealed the win when CB [[Chris Houston (American football)|Chris Houston]] returned it 10&nbsp;yards for a touchdown.<ref name=\"Falcons back\"/>\n\nWith their twelfth consecutive loss, the Chiefs fell to 0\u20133.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Week 4: vs. Denver Broncos===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Broncos\n| Host = '''Chiefs'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 10 | V3 = 3 | V4 = 6\n| H1 = 6 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 17\n|date= September 28, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance = 74,623\n| Weather = 74&nbsp;\u00b0F (Mostly Sunny)\n| Referee = [[Mike Carey (American football)|Mike Carey]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| FirstEntry = yes\n| Quarter = Q1 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 09:05 | Team = KC | Event = [[Nick Novak]] 23&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 3\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 04:38 | Team = KC | Event = Novak 21&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 6\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q2 | QuarterEntries = 3\n| Time = 08:53 | Team = DEN | Event = [[Brandon Marshall]] 16&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] ([[Matt Prater]] kick) | Score = DEN 6\u20137\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 02:43 | Team = KC | Event = [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] 1&nbsp;yd TD run (Novak kick) | Score = KC 13\u20137\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:11 | Team = DEN | Event = Prater 53&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 13\u201310\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q3 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 12:13 | Team = DEN | Event = Prater 51&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = Tied 13\u201313\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 08:43 | Team = KC | Event = Novak 43&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 16\u201313\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q4 | QuarterEntries = 5\n| Time = 12:40 | Team = KC | Event = [[Tony Gonzalez]] 10&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Damon Huard]] (Novak kick) | Score = KC 23\u201313\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 07:58 | Team = DEN | Event = Prater 22&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 23\u201316\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 03:49 | Team = KC | Event = Novak 33&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 26\u201316\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 02:06 | Team = DEN | Event = Prater 33&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 23\u201319\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 01:37 | Team = KC | Event = [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] 16&nbsp;yd TD run (Novak kick) | Score = KC 33\u201319\n| LastEntry = yes\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Chiefs hosted the 3\u20130 Broncos in hopes of winning their first game of the season.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\">Associated Press. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=280928012 Johnson rushes for 198&nbsp;yards, two TDs as Chiefs' 12-game losing streak ends] ''ESPN.com'', September 28, 2008.</ref> The Chiefs' offense, averaging fewer than 11 points a game, turned early touchdown opportunities into short field goals.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/>\n\nIn its first two possessions, Denver's league-leading offense had a turnover, a sack and a shanked punt.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> Larry Johnson ran a career-long 65-yard run to the 21&nbsp;yard line on the game's second play.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> Kansas City had first-and-goal from the 9, but only managed a field goal.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> The field goal gave Kansas City their first lead in 22 quarters, since the team's lead against the Titans on December 16, 2007.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/>\n\nWith QB Damon Huard at the helm, the Chiefs' offense allowed no turnovers and scored more points in one game (33) than their first three games of the season combined (32).<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> Denver's running defense was noticeably weak and allowed Chiefs RB Larry Johnson to run for 198&nbsp;yards.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> Johnson also tallied his first 2 touchdown game in over two years. Denver allowed four turnovers,<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> which the Chiefs capitalized on three. Chiefs TE Tony Gonzalez scored one touchdown and finished the game within three yards shy of tying [[Shannon Sharpe]]'s all-time receiving record (10,060).<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/>\n\nThe win was Kansas City's first since a victory over Oakland on October 21, 2007.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/> Johnson tallied his 29th career 100-yard rushing game and his fifth against Denver.<ref name=\"Johnson rushes\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 5: at Carolina Panthers===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Panthers'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 0\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 14 | H3 = 10 | H4 = 3\n| Date = October 5, 2008\n| Location = [[Bank of America Stadium]], [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 2:51\n| Attendance = 72,319\n| Weather = 80&nbsp;\u00b0F (Sunny)\n| Referee = [[Terry McAulay]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Kevin Harlan]] & [[Rich Gannon]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their stunning home win over the Broncos, the Chiefs flew to [[Bank of America Stadium]] for a Week 5 interconference duel with the [[Carolina Panthers]].<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\">\n{{cite news | title=Williams' career-best game helps Panthers blank Chiefs | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29590&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG5 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=NFL | date=October 5, 2008 | accessdate=November 27, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211052706/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29590&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG5 | archivedate=December 11, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> In the first quarter, Kansas City trailed as RB [[DeAngelo Williams]] got a 10-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\"/> In the second quarter, the Chiefs continued to trail as Williams caught a 25-yard TD pass from QB [[Jake Delhomme]], along with getting a 32-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\"/> In the second quarter, Carolina kicker [[John Kasay]] missed a 32-yard field goal, along with Delhomme completing a 47-yard TD pass to WR [[Muhsin Muhammad]].<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\"/> In the fourth quarter, the Panthers sealed the win with Kasay nailing a 43-yard field goal.<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\"/> TE [[Tony Gonzalez]] (3 receptions for 17&nbsp;yards) became the NFL's all-time leader in career receiving yards for a tight end with 10,063&nbsp;yards.<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\"/>\n\nWith the shutout loss, the Chiefs fell to 1\u20134.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Bye Week \u2013 Gonzalez and Johnson controversies===\n[[File:Larry Johnson KC Chiefs.jpg|thumb|right|Larry Johnson's legal troubles became public knowledge during the Chiefs' bye week.]]\n\nTE [[Tony Gonzalez]] met with Chiefs GM [[Carl Peterson]] during the bye week and inquired about a trade to a playoff contender.<ref name=\"Chiefs willing\">{{cite web | title=Source: Chiefs willing to listen to offers for record-setting TE Gonzalez | last=Smith | first=Michael | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3638551 | work=ESPN | date=2008-10-12 | accessdate=October 21, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081020232347/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3638551| archivedate= October 20, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Gonzalez, who had always said he would like to end his career with the Chiefs,<ref name=\"Chiefs willing\"/> voiced his desire to play for a Super Bowl contending team and the rebuilding Chiefs would like to acquire extra draft picks.<ref name=\"Chiefs willing\"/> Buffalo, Atlanta, Green Bay, Philadelphia, and the New York Giants had been in contact with the Chiefs regarding Gonzalez.<ref name=\"Chiefs willing\"/> The Giants were considered to be the front-runners, but showed \"lukewarm\" interest.<ref name=\"Gonzalez wants out\"/> The Packers offered a third round draft choice, but the deal was not finalized, and Gonzalez remained with the Chiefs after the trading deadline passed.<ref name=\"Gonzalez tells\">{{cite web | title=Gonzalez tells teammates he's not bitter about failed trade request | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3645516 | work=ESPN | date=October 16, 2008 | accessdate=October 21, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081018172018/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3645516| archivedate= October 18, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nRB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] was charged with simple assault for allegedly pushing a woman at a Kansas City nightclub in February, the third time he has faced assault charges against a woman.<ref name=\"Johnson charged\">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3642364 Chiefs RB Johnson charged with pushing woman on side of head in February] ''ESPN.com'', October 14, 2008.</ref> Johnson was also reportedly offered by the Chiefs for a trade.<ref name=\"Gonzalez wants out\">{{cite web|title=Glazer: Gonzalez wants out of K.C. |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/8668292/Glazer:-Gonzalez-wants-out-of-K.C.?CMP=OTC-K9B140813162&ATT=5 |last=Glazer |first=Jay |work=Fox Sports |date=October 12, 2008 |accessdate=October 21, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016032028/http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/8668292/Glazer%3A-Gonzalez-wants-out-of-K.C.?CMP=OTC-K9B140813162&ATT=5 |archivedate=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Days later, coach Herm Edwards ruled Johnson out of the Chiefs' upcoming game against Tennessee as a result of a violation of team rules. Edwards stated that it was not in response to Johnson's legal troubles, but instead of insubordination.<ref name=\"Johnson's discipline\">{{cite web | title=Source: Johnson's discipline in response to pattern of behavior | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3647097 | work=ESPN | date=October 18, 2008 | accessdate=October 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDays later, reports surfaced that Johnson was under investigation for allegedly telling a woman that he was going to kill her boyfriend then spat in her face at Kansas City's Club Blonde on October 10, just four days prior to his court hearing for a separate incident.<ref name=\"Johnson under\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs' Johnson under investigation for latest incident involving a woman | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3654308 | work=ESPN | date=October 20, 2008 | accessdate=October 21, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081023102659/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3654308| archivedate= October 23, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Johnson's pattern of behavior could lead to a possible suspension under the [[National Football League player conduct controversy|NFL's personal conduct policy]].<ref name=\"Johnson under\"/> Johnson made a public apology on October 22.<ref>[http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/10/22/statement_by_rb_larry_johnson/ Statement by RB Larry Johnson] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025055530/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/10/22/statement_by_rb_larry_johnson/ |date=October 25, 2008 }} ''Kansas City Chiefs official website'', October 22, 2008.</ref> As a result of his October 10 incident, Johnson was de-activated for the Chiefs' game against the [[New York Jets]].<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\">Associated Press. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3658139 Johnson will not play for second straight week; Thigpen to start at QB] ''ESPN.com'', October 23, 2008.</ref> As a result, Johnson was charged with simple assault for the second time in two weeks.<ref name=\"spitting in woman's face\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs' Johnson charged for spitting in woman's face, won't play for now | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3667069 | publisher=ESPN | date=October 28, 2008 | accessdate=October 28, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030081901/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3667069| archivedate= October 30, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The Chiefs indicated that Johnson would meet with NFL commissioner [[Roger Goodell]] and would not play \"for the foreseeable future.\"<ref name=\"spitting in woman's face\"/> Goodell subsequently suspended Johnson for the Chiefs' Week 10 game against the Chargers.<ref name=\"Johnson suspended\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs running back will sit out Week 10 for violating NFL conduct policy | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3675871 | work=ESPN | date=November 2, 2008 | accessdate=November 29, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081205115105/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3675871| archivedate= December 5, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 7: vs. Tennessee Titans===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Titans'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 10 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 3 | V4 = 14\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 0 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 10\n| Date = October 19, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 2:57\n| Attendance = 74,200\n| Weather = 63&nbsp;\u00b0F (Sunny)\n| Referee = [[Gene Steratore]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]] & [[Steve Tasker]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their bye week, the Chiefs went home for a Week 7 duel with the undefeated [[Tennessee Titans]].<ref name=\"Titans extend\">{{cite news | title=Titans extend winning streak as Chiefs lose game, Croyle | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29621&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG7&override=true | agency=Associated Press | publisher=NFL | date=October 19, 2008 | accessdate=November 27, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023113330/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29621&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG7&override=true | archivedate=October 23, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the first quarter, Kansas City trailed early as Titans kicker [[Rob Bironas]] got a 49-yard field goal, along with RB [[LenDale White]] getting a 6-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> In the second quarter, Tennessee increased its lead with White getting a 2-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> In the third quarter, the Chiefs continued to struggle as Bironas got a 46-yard field goal.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> In the fourth quarter, the Titans began to put the game out of reach as White got an 80-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> Kansas City would finally get on the board as kicker [[Nick Novak]] got a 26-yard field goal.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> Tennessee would seal the win as RB [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]] got a 66-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/> The Chiefs would end the game with QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] getting a 14-yard TD run.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/>\n\nWith the loss, Kansas City fell to 1\u20135.\n\nDuring the game starting QB [[Brodie Croyle]] (9/10 for 63&nbsp;yards) suffered a sprained knee in the second quarter. Also, veteran QB [[Damon Huard]] (9/16 for 96&nbsp;yards) later left the game in the fourth with an injured thumb. Both would be placed on injured reserve, ending their seasons.<ref name=\"Titans extend\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n====Implementing the spread offense====\n[[File:081116Saints-Chiefs02.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Chan Gailey implemented a new offense based almost entirely on [[spread offense|spread]] and [[wildcat formation|wildcat]] [[Formation (American football)|formations]].<ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\"/><ref name=\"Spread changes\">{{cite web | title=Spread changes options for Chiefs | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?id=3717080 | last=Chadiha | first=Jeffri | publisher=ESPN | date=November 21, 2008 | accessdate=November 26, 2008}}</ref> Against the Saints, RB Larry Johnson lines up as the quarterback.]]\n\nTo help Tyler Thigpen prepare for the game against the Jets, the Chiefs implemented the [[spread offense]] to help Thigpen and the rest of the younger players play to the best of their abilities, and also following the absence of RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] due to suspension.<ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\"/><ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> The Chiefs made a huge gamble by doing so, as most in the NFL believe that a [[spread offense]] cannot work in professional football, and also head coach Herman Edwards was traditionally in favor of more conservative, run-oriented game plans.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> Prior to the Chiefs implementing the spread offense, Thigpen had been playing erratically with the Chiefs, and he suddenly became poised and effective running the new offense.<ref name=\"A copycat game\">{{cite web | title=A copycat game | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ | last=Rand | first=Jonathan | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | date=December 2, 2008 | accessdate=December 3, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081206125042/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ |archivedate = December 6, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 8: at New York Jets===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Jets'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 14 | V3 = 3 | V4 = 7\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 7\n| Date = October 26, 2008\n| Location = [[Giants Stadium|The Meadowlands]], [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:04\n| Attendance = 78,037\n| Weather = 59&nbsp;\u00b0F (Clear)\n| Referee = [[Pete Morelli]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to rebound from their loss to the Titans, the Chiefs flew to [[Giants Stadium|The Meadowlands]] for a Week 8 duel with the [[New York Jets]].  Due to the season-ending injuries to QB's [[Brodie Croyle]] and [[Damon Huard]], [[Tyler Thigpen]] made his second career start.<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\"/> Thigpen became the starting quarterback by default.<ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\">{{cite web | title=Breaking the Mold | url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ | last=Rand | first=Jonathan | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | date=November 13, 2008 | accessdate=November 14, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090110191420/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ |archivedate = January 10, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the first quarter, Kansas City trailed early as Jets QB [[Brett Favre]] completed an 18-yard TD pass to RB [[Leon Washington]].  In the second quarter, the Chiefs tied the game as Thigpen completed a 19-yard TD pass to TE [[Tony Gonzalez]].  New York responded with Washington getting a 60-yard TD run, yet Kansas City closed out the half with Thigpen completed an 11-yard TD pass to WR [[Mark Bradley]].\n\nIn the third quarter, the Chiefs took the lead as rookie kicker [[Connor Barth]] nailed a 30-yard field goal, yet the Jets regained the lead with RB [[Thomas Jones (American football)|Thomas Jones]] getting a 1-yard TD run.  In the fourth quarter, Kansas City took the lead again as rookie CB [[Brandon Flowers (American football)|Brandon Flowers]] returned an interception 91&nbsp;yards for a touchdown.  However, New York got the last laugh as Favre completed a 15-yard TD pass to WR [[Laveranues Coles]].\n\nWith the loss, the Chiefs fell to 1\u20136.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 9: vs. Tampa Bay Buccaneers===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Buccaneers'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 13 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 14 | VOT = 3 | Total 30\n| H1 = 14 | H2 = 10 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 3 | HOT = 0 | Total 27\n| Date = November 2, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:28\n| Attendance = 74,045\n| Weather = 69&nbsp;\u00b0F (Sunny)\n| Referee = [[Ed Hochuli]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Ron Pitts]], [[Tony Boselli]], & [[Charissa Thompson]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on Fox|Fox]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe game started well for the Chiefs who jumped out to a 24\u20133 lead, which included a \"trick\" touchdown pass from [[Mark Bradley]] (wide receiver) to [[Tyler Thigpen]] (quarterback).  The momentum started to change when the Buccaneers ran a punt return for a touchdown and added a late field goal to cut the deficit to a 24\u201313 margin.  In the fourth quarter, Tampa Bay picked up a late touchdown on a fumble to bring the game to a 27\u201325 deficit.  They converted the two-point conversion to tie the game at 27\u201327.  In overtime, the Buccaneers systematically ran the ball to the 30-yard line and then kicked the winning field goal to capture a 30\u201327 victory.  It was the biggest margin they have overcome in their history.  The loss was the Chiefs' 16th in the past 17 games.\n\nWith their 4th-straight loss, Kansas City fell to 1\u20137.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 10: at San Diego Chargers===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Chargers'''\n| V1 = 7 | V2 = 6 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 6 | Total 19\n| H1 = 0 | H2 = 6 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 7 | Total 20\n| Date = November 9, 2008\n| Location = [[Qualcomm Stadium]], [[San Diego, California]]\n| StartTime = 4:15&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 3:15&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:06\n| Attendance = 67,510\n| Weather = 62&nbsp;\u00b0F (Cloudy)\n| Referee = [[Ron Winter]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]] & [[Steve Tasker]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Chiefs took an early lead on a 30-yard pass from [[Tyler Thigpen]] to [[Mark Bradley]].  The Chiefs defense continued to show improvement in the red zone, limiting the Chargers to two field goals instead of two touch downs.  At the end of the first half, Thigpen threw a pass to 34&nbsp;yard touchdown pass to [[Tony Gonzalez]]. However, the extra point snap was botched and an attempt at a quick pass failed.\n\nThe Chargers controlled the second half better than the first, scoring two touchdowns and leading the Chiefs by 7 at the end of the fourth quarter.  The Chiefs' final drive ended with a 3-yard touchdown pass to Gonzalez. A 1-point PAT would tie the game. However, [[Herm Edwards]] told Thigpen to go for two, explaining in a post-game interview that the defense was too beat up for overtime play.  The resulting two-point conversion ended in an incomplete pass.  The Chiefs lost by one point.\n\nWith the loss, Kansas City fell to 1\u20138.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 11: vs. New Orleans Saints===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Saints'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 3 | V2 = 10 | V3 = 14 | V4 = 3 | Total 30\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 3 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 7 | Total 20\n| Date = November 16, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:03\n| Attendance = 74,159\n| Weather = 53&nbsp;\u00b0F (Sunny)\n| Referee = [[John Parry (American football official)|John Parry]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Thom Brennaman]] & [[Brian Billick]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on Fox|Fox]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to snap their five-game losing streak, the Chiefs went home for a Week 11 interconference duel with the [[New Orleans Saints]].  In the first quarter, Kansas City struck first as QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] completed a 6-yard TD pass to WR [[Dwayne Bowe]].  The Saints would respond with kicker [[Garrett Hartley]] getting a 30-yard field goal.  In the second quarter, New Orleans took the lead as RB [[Deuce McAllister]] got a 1-yard TD run.  The Chiefs would answer with rookie kicker [[Connor Barth]] getting a 20-yard field goal.  The Saints closed out the half with Hartley making a 23-yard field goal.\n\nIn the third quarter, New Orleans increased their lead with QB [[Drew Brees]] completing a 47-yard TD pass to WR [[Lance Moore]].  Kansas City replied with Barth making a 21-yard field goal, yet the Saints answered with RB [[Pierre Thomas (American football)|Pierre Thomas]] getting a 1-yard TD run.  In the fourth quarter, the Chiefs tried to rally as Thigpen hooked up with Bowe again on a 5-yard TD pass.  However, New Orleans pulled away with Hartley nailing a 35-yard field goal.\n\nWith their sixth-straight loss, Kansas City fell to 1\u20139.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Chiefs vs. Saints.jpg|[[Connor Barth]] kicks off against New Orleans; [[Wallace Gilberry]] in background\nFile:081116Saints-Chiefs.jpg|Tyler Thigpen leads the Chiefs' offense in a shotgun formation\n</gallery>\n\n===Week 12: vs. Buffalo Bills===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Bills'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 7 | V2 = 23 | V3 = 17 | V4 = 7 | Total 0\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 10 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 7 | Total 0\n| Date = November 23, 2008\n| Location = [[Arrowhead Stadium]], [[Kansas City, Missouri]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:17\n| Attendance = 73,584\n| Weather = 50&nbsp;\u00b0F (Mostly Sunny)\n| Referee = [[Bill Leavy]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Ian Eagle]] & [[Solomon Wilcots]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Chiefs hosted the 5\u20135 Bills, losers of their past four games, on November 23. Tyler Thigpen had his first bad game in five outings in the Chiefs' 54\u201331 loss.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\"/> Thigpen's three turnovers\u2013two interceptions and one lost fumble\u2013led to 20 points by the Bills.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\"/> Despite the turnovers, Thigpen also threw for 240&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\"/>\n\nThe 54 points by Buffalo were the Chiefs' most allowed in a game in the franchise's history.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\"/> With the loss, the Chiefs fell to a 1\u201310 record, their 20th loss in 21 games.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 13: at Oakland Raiders===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Chiefs'''\n| Host = Raiders\n| V1 = 3 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 10 | Total 20\n| H1 = 3 | H2 = 0 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 3 | Total 13\n| Date = November 30, 2008\n| Location =  [[Oakland\u2013Alameda County Coliseum]]\n| StartTime = 4:15&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] / 1:15&nbsp;PM [[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:00\n| Attendance = 61,379\n| Weather = 59&nbsp;\u00b0F (Partly Cloudy)\n| Referee = [[Peter Morelli]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Bill Macatee]] and [[Steve Beuerlein]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Raiders hosted the Chiefs at Oakland\u2013Alameda County Coliseum on November 30.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\">{{cite news | title=Johnson's 2-yard plunge lifts Chiefs over woeful Raiders | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281130013 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN | date=November 30, 2008 | accessdate=December 1, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081202135057/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281130013| archivedate= December 2, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The game began with both teams exchanging field goals to tie the game at 3.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The Raiders lined up to kick another field goal, but instead elected to run a fake field goal, which was fumbled and recovered by Chiefs CB [[Maurice Leggett]] and returned for a touchdown.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The Chiefs led the game 10\u20133 at halftime.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> In the third quarter, the Raiders tied the game at 10 with a touchdown by RB [[Justin Fargas]].<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> With the Chiefs backed up to their own 9 following a punt, QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] led the Chiefs's offense down the field and capped the drive with a hand-off to RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] for a 2-yard touchdown.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> On Oakland's next possession, Justin Fargas fumbled the football which eventually set up a Chiefs field goal.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The Raiders attempted to get back in the game with a field goal by K [[Sebastian Janikowski]], but the Chiefs held possession and ran out the clock for the remainder of the game.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The Chiefs managed to snap their seven-game losing streak by beating the Raiders 20\u201313.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> It was Kansas City's sixth consecutive victory at Oakland\u2013Alameda County Coliseum.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The victory was Tyler Thigpen's first as the Chiefs' starting quarterback.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/>\n\nWith the win, Kansas City improved to 2\u201310.\n\n===Week 14: at Denver Broncos===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Broncos'''\n| V1 = 10 | V2 = 7 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 0 | Total 17\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 7 | Total 24\n| Date = December 7, 2008\n| Location =  [[Invesco Field at Mile High]]\n| StartTime = 4:05&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] / 1:05&nbsp;PM [[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 2:55\n| Attendance = 75,187\n| Weather = 64&nbsp;\u00b0F (Partly Cloudy)\n| Referee = [[Scott Green (American football official)|Scott Green]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Bill Macatee]] and [[Steve Beuerlein]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nFresh off their divisional road win over the Raiders, the Chiefs flew to [[Invesco Field at Mile High]] for a Week 14 AFC West rematch with the [[Denver Broncos]].  In the first quarter, Kansas City got the early lead as rookie kicker [[Connor Barth]] got a 26-yard field goal, while rookie CB [[Maurice Leggett]] returned an interception 27&nbsp;yards for a touchdown.  The Broncos would with RB [[Peyton Hillis]] getting an 18-yard touchdown run.  The Chiefs answered in the second quarter with QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] completing a 13-yard touchdown pass to TE [[Tony Gonzalez]], yet Denver closed out the half with QB [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] completing a 12-yard touchdown pass to WR [[Brandon Marshall]].\n\nIn the third quarter, the Broncos tied the game with kicker [[Matt Prater]] nailing a 33-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, Denver took the lead as Cutler hooked up with Marshall again on a 6-yard touchdown pass.  Kansas City tried to rally, but the Broncos' defense was too much to overcome.\n\nWith the loss, the Chiefs fell to 2\u201311.\n\n===Week 15: vs. San Diego Chargers===\n[[File:2008 Chargers.jpg|thumb|[[San Diego Chargers]]' [[Clinton Hart]] stops the Chiefs' last attempt at winning the game, knocking the ball into [[Quentin Jammer]]'s arms]]\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Chargers'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 3 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 12 | Total 22\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 7 | H3 = 7 | H4 = 0 | Total 21\n| Date = December 14, 2008\n| Location =  [[Arrowhead Stadium]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:28\n| Attendance = 73,842\n| Weather = 36&nbsp;\u00b0F (Cloudy)\n| Referee = [[Carl Cheffers]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Ian Eagle]] and [[Solomon Wilcots]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| FirstEntry = yes\n| Quarter = Q1 | QuarterEntries = 1\n| Time = 05:05 | Team = KC | Event = [[Tony Gonzalez]] 4&nbsp;yd TD pass from [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] ([[Connor Barth]] kick) | Score = KC 7\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q2 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 02:56 | Team = KC | Event = [[Dwayne Bowe]] 1&nbsp;yd pass from [[Tyler Thigpen]] (Barth kick) | Score = KC 14\u20130\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:14 | Team = SD | Event = [[Nate Kaeding]] 32&nbsp;yd field goal | Score = KC 14\u20133\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q3 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 12:39 | Team = KC | Event = Thigpen 3&nbsp;yd TD run (Barth kick) | Score = KC 21\u20133\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 08:33 | Team = SD | Event = [[LaDanian Tomlinson]] 6&nbsp;yd run (Kaeding kick) | Score = KC 21\u201310\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Quarter = Q4 | QuarterEntries = 2\n| Time = 01:19 | Team = SD | Event = [[Malcolm Floyd]] 4&nbsp;yd TD pass (2-point conversion failed) | Score = KC 21\u201316\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry\n| Time = 00:40 | Team = SD | Event = [[Vincent Jackson]] 10&nbsp;yd pass (2-point conversion failed) | Score = SD 22\u201321\n| LastEntry = yes\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Chiefs hosted the 5\u20138 Chargers on December 14, hoping to end their slim playoff chances.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\">{{cite news | title=Chargers keep slim playoff hopes alive with rally in Kansas City | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29744&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG15%20Recap | agency=Associated Press | publisher=NFL.com | date=December 14, 2008 | accessdate=December 15, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109055902/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29744&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG15%20Recap | archivedate=January 9, 2009 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Temperatures which hovered in the low 60s when early-arriving fans first showed up plunged into the 20s by the end of the game.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> The Chiefs dominated the game early, leading 14\u20133 at halftime. Chiefs quarterback Tyler Thigpen threw for one touchdown and ran for another for the Chiefs and was 19-for-28 for 171&nbsp;yards.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/>\n\nThe Chargers had three turnovers and, perhaps more embarrassing, gave up three sacks to the NFL's worst pass rush.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> Tamba Hali had two sacks and caused two fumbles for a Chiefs defense that hadn't gotten a sack since playing San Diego four games ago.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> The three sacks pushed Kansas City's season total to a league-low nine, and the Chiefs need five in their last two games to avoid tying the NFL record for fewest in a season.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> Five of the sacks from the season have come against San Diego.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/>\n\nLeading into the fourth quarter, Kansas City led 21\u201310, but allowed 11 points in the final 79&nbsp;seconds of the game to lose 22\u201321.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> The Chiefs, despite having an 18-point lead, used up all three time-outs.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/> The victory sealed a season sweep for San Diego over Kansas City, with both victories ending in a one-point margin.<ref name=\"Chargers keep\"/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:081214Chargers-Chiefs01.jpg|Action in the week 15 clash\nFile:081214Chargers-Chiefs02.jpg|The Chiefs' defense takes on the Chargers offense\nFile:081214Chargers-Chiefs03.jpg|A passing play by Kansas City\nFile:081214Chargers-Chiefs04.jpg|Although the announced attendance was 73,842, Arrowhead Stadium was noticeably empty throughout most of the game\n</gallery>\n\n====Resignation of Carl Peterson====\nThe day after the Chiefs' loss to San Diego, Chiefs owner [[Clark Hunt]] announced the resignation of [[Carl Peterson]] from all positions held (general manager, vice president, and chief executive officer) effective at the end of the season.<ref name=\"Chiefs GM Peterson\"/><ref name=\"press conference\">{{cite web | title=Chairman of the Board Clark Hunt Press Conference on the resignation of Carl Peterson | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/15/chairman_of_the_board_clark_hunt_pc/ | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | date=December 15, 2008 | accessdate=December 15, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081218225808/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/15/chairman_of_the_board_clark_hunt_pc/ |archivedate = December 18, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\">{{cite news | title=Chiefs' Carl Peterson resigns; Edwards' future uncertain | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/chiefs/2008-12-15-peterson-out_N.htm?csp=34 | work=USA Today | agency=Associated Press | date=December 15, 2008 | accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe official press release stated that Peterson resigned, but Hunt had said the conversation had been on-going throughout the season.<ref name=\"press conference\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> Hunt said his decision to relieve Peterson of duties was not based on what happened the previous day, when the Chiefs lost an 11-point lead in the final 73&nbsp;seconds and were beaten 22\u201321 by San Diego, dropping their record to 2\u201312.<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> Hunt also said that the fate of head coach [[Herman Edwards]] would be settled after the season.<ref name=\"press conference\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> Hunt said he would split the duties previously held by Peterson and have someone in charge of the business side and someone else in charge of football for the franchise.<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> Hunt said he plans on hiring someone from outside the organization.<ref name=\"press conference\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Week 16: vs. Miami Dolphins===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = '''Dolphins'''\n| Host = Chiefs\n| V1 = 10 | V2 = 14 | V3 = 7 | V4 = 7 | Total 38\n| H1 = 7 | H2 = 21 | H3 = 3 | H4 = 0 | Total 31\n| Date = December 21, 2008\n| Location =  [[Arrowhead Stadium]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 3:17\n| Attendance = 73,869\n| Weather = 10&nbsp;\u00b0F (Sunny, breezy, \u221212&nbsp;\u00b0F wind chill)\n| Referee = [[Jeff Triplette]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Dick Enberg]], [[Randy Cross]], & [[Dan Fouts]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nKansas City hosted the [[Miami Dolphins]] in the second-coldest game ever held at [[Arrowhead Stadium]] on December 21 with the game-time temperature at 10&nbsp;\u00b0F and a [[wind chill]] at \u221212&nbsp;\u00b0F.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\">{{cite news | title=Pennington-led Dolphins beat cold, Chiefs to stay in playoff hunt | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29756&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG16 | agency=Associated Press | date=December 21, 2008 | accessdate=December 21, 2008 | publisher=NFL.com | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222140234/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29756&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG16 | archivedate=December 22, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was the coldest conditions that Miami had ever played in.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> Miami scored first on the opening drive with a touchdown by WR [[Ted Ginn, Jr.]].<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> Despite trailing 10\u20130 early in the game, Tyler Thigpen led the Chiefs to a 28\u201324 lead by halftime.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> The Chiefs failed to score a touchdown in the second half of the game, only managing a field goal by [[Connor Barth]].<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> The Dolphins broke a 31\u201331 tie with a touchdown by TE [[Anthony Fasano]] with 4:08 remaining in the game.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> With just over a minute remaining, Chiefs LB [[Demorrio Williams]] forced and recovered a fumble to give the Chiefs another chance to tie the game.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> A failed drive capped off by Thigpen's third interception helped Miami run out the clock.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> Thigpen threw a career best 320&nbsp;yards with two touchdowns, but also threw three interceptions.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> TE [[Tony Gonzalez]] became the first Chiefs player and first NFL tight end to record four 1,000&nbsp;yard receiving seasons.<ref name=\"Pennington-led\"/> The game also marked the last time Gonzalez played in Arrowhead Stadium as a member of the Chiefs, due to his trade to the Falcons following the season.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs01.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs02.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs03.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs04.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs05.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs06.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs07.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs08.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs09.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs10.JPG\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs11.jpg\nFile:081221Dolphins-Chiefs12.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n===Week 17: at Cincinnati Bengals===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Visitor = Chiefs\n| Host = '''Bengals'''\n| V1 = 0 | V2 = 0 | V3 = 0 | V4 = 6 | Total 6\n| H1 = 3 | H2 = 10 | H3 = 0 | H4 = 3 | Total 16\n| Date = December 28, 2008\n| Location =  [[Paul Brown Stadium]]\n| StartTime = 1:00&nbsp;PM [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] / 12:00&nbsp;PM [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| ElapsedTime = 2:55\n| Attendance = 63,984\n| Weather = 43&nbsp;\u00b0F\n| Referee = [[Bill Carollo]]\n| TVAnnouncers = [[Bill Macatee]] and [[Steve Beuerlein]]\n| TVStation = [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Bengals hosted the Chiefs for both teams' final game of the 2008 season on December 28.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\">{{cite news | title=Chiefs' Johnson wants out after season-ending loss to Bengals | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29771&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG17&override=true | agency=Associated Press | publisher=NFL.com | date=December 28, 2008 | accessdate=December 28, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231130224/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29771&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG17&override=true | archivedate=December 31, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Entering the game, the Bengals had a 3\u201311\u20131 record and the Chiefs had a 2\u201313 record.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> While there was speculation over the job status of [[Herm Edwards]] as head coach entering the off-season, RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] voiced his intention to seek a trade.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> Cincinnati completely dominated the game.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> They outrushed the Chiefs 204&nbsp;yards to 31&nbsp;yards.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> Kansas City could only manage two first downs in the first half.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/>\n\nThe Chiefs did not get closer than the Bengals' 37-yard line until their final drive, which ended with TE [[Tony Gonzalez]]'s 5-yard touchdown catch from QB [[Tyler Thigpen]] with 2:20 left in the game.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> A two-point conversion attempt failed, and the Bengals effectively held the lead for the remainder of the game.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> The Chiefs' defense had one sack in the game to finish the season with 10\u2013the fewest in the NFL since the league started recording team sacks in 1960.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/> The team surpassed the 1982 Baltimore Colts' record of 11 sacks.<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/>\n\n==Standings==\n{{2008 AFC West standings}}\n\n==Season statistics==\nAll statistics through the completion of the 2008 NFL season (December 28, 2008).\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Offense===\n'''Yards per game:''' 314.6 (#22 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\">{{cite web | title=NFL Team Stats: 2008 (Offense) | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?stat=team&sort=ppg&pos=off&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008 | publisher=ESPN.com | accessdate=December 28, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217172229/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?stat=team&sort=ppg&pos=off&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008| archivedate= December 17, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n'''Total yards in season:''' 4,719 (#22 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Points per game:''' 19.0 (#25 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Points in season:''' 285 (#25 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Quarterback rating:'''\n* Tyler Thigpen (11 starts) \u2013 75.8<ref name=\"Quarterback ratings\">{{cite web | title=NFL Team Stats: 2008 (Quarterbacks) | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?stat=pass&sort=rat&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008 | publisher=ESPN.com | accessdate=December 28, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217023545/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?stat=pass&sort=rat&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008| archivedate= December 17, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n'''Rushing yards in season:''' 1,779 (#11 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Rushing yards per game:''' 118.6 (#11 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Passing yards in season:''' 2,940 (#19 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n'''Passing yards per game:''' 196.0 (#19 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: offense\"/>\n\n{{Col-break|gap=3em}}\n\n===Defense===\n'''Yards allowed per game:''' 397.5 (#31 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: defense\">{{cite web | title=NFL Team Stats: 2008 (Defense)|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?sort=ypg&stat=team&pos=def&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008 | publisher=ESPN.com | accessdate=December 28, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217142036/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/statistics?sort=ypg&stat=team&pos=def&league=nfl&season=2&year=2008| archivedate= December 17, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n'''Rushing yards allowed per game:''' 155.9 (#30 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: defense\"/>\n\n'''Passing yards allowed per game:''' 241.5 (#30 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: defense\"/>\n\n'''Points allowed in season:''' 424 (#30 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: defense\"/>\n\n'''Points allowed per game:''' 28.3 (#30 in NFL)<ref name=\"statistics: defense\"/>\n\n'''Fewest quarterback sacks, team:''' 10 ('''#32 in NFL\u2013all-time record''')<ref name=\"Johnson wants\"/>\n\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|2008 Kansas City Chiefs season}}\n{{clear}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Kansas City Chiefs}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs seasons}}\n{{2008 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2008 Kansas City Chiefs Season}}\n[[Category:2008 National Football League season by team|Kansas City]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs seasons]]\n[[Category:2008 in sports in Missouri|Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "Sm999", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed two dead links. \"Breaking the mold\" and \"A copycat game\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season"}
{"title_page": "Anton Loginov", "text_new": "'''Anton Loginov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432}}, born '''Mikhail Osipovich Loginov''', \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432; 1882\u20131963) was a Russian [[Bolsheviks|Bolshevik]] Revolutionary, Communist Party member, journalist,<ref>[http://rosgenea.ru/?a=12&p=15&r=4&s=%CB%EE%E3%E8%ED%EE%E2 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref> writer, [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] publicist, and propagandist of atheism.<ref>[[Atheistic Dictionary]] / [http://\u0432\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0435.\u0440\u0444/\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439-\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c-2/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nLoginov was a member of the [[Russian Social Democratic Labour Party]] starting in 1902 and had the party nickname \"Anton\".<ref>[http://rosgenea.ru/?a=12&p=15&r=4&s=%CB%EE%E3%E8%ED%EE%E2 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref> He was also a member of the Tiflis City Party Committee and the Soviet of Soldiers' Deputies starting in 1918.<ref>\u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0432 \"\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0435\".: \u0412\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f, /  1970 -   /  \u0421. 341</ref> From 1902 to 1912 he led illegal party work in Moscow and participated in many revolutions such as the First Russian revolution in Moscow and the October Revolution of 1917 in [[Tiflis]].\n\nLoginov was a born speaker and a witty polemist. [[Lenin]] learned of his ability to speak with the masses in a simple and understandable language, to attract interesting material and witty answers to questions. He advised Loginov to engage in anti-religious propaganda. From the beginning of the 1920s Loginov devoted himself entirely to atheistic work, and trained qualified personnel in the anti-religious campaign.<ref>\u0418\u0434\u0435\u0438 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0436\u0438\u0432\u0443\u0442 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0442  / \u0420\u0435\u0434. \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0438\u044f: \u0434\u043e\u0446. \u042f. \u041c. \u0414\u0430\u0445\u0438\u044f (\u043e\u0442\u0432. \u0440\u0435\u0434.) [\u0438 \u0434\u0440.] ; \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440. \u0433\u043e\u0441. \u0443\u043d-\u0442 \u0438\u043c. \u0410. \u0410. \u0416\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430. - \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 : [\u0431. \u0438.], 1970. - 269 \u0441.; / \u0421. 371, 372</ref> The Moscow Party had appointed Loginov to [[:ru:\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f, \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430|Kostelovskaia]]'s place on the Anti-religious Commission in March 1925, and by 1926 he was a leading [[League of Militant Atheists|League]] official.<ref>[http://bookre.org/reader?file=1082383&pg=67 Daniel Peris. Storming the Heavens: The Soviet League of the Militant Godless/ Cornell University Press, 1998 / p. 54]</ref>  He was a member of the bureau of the district party committee, a member of the MK RCP (b), chairman of the Moscow and Central Soviet of Atheists, deputy People's Commissar of Communications, and editor of the newspaper and magazine \"[[Bezbozhnik (newspaper)|Bezbozhnik]]\".<ref>[http://rosgenea.ru/?a=12&p=15&r=4&s=%CB%EE%E3%E8%ED%EE%E2 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref>\n\nIn the 1920s Loginov participated in disputes with representatives of the clergy. He focused on exposing the counter-revolutionary activity of churchmen, the antiscientific and reactionary essence of religion, and the class implications of religious morality. Loginov was the author of many articles and brochures on atheism and on religion.<ref>[[Atheistic Dictionary]] / [http://\u0432\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0435.\u0440\u0444/\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439-\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c-2/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref> His book was published under the name \"Anton Loginov\". Typical of a pamphlet aimed at the countryside was Anton Loginov's \"The Godless: the Best Friend of the Peasant\" (1925). We do not want to take religion away from you, explained Loginov, we just want you to give it up. \"And what do you replace it with\", he has the peasant ask  (quite realistically)? His answer \u201cEvil does not have to be replaced, but simply rooted out. That is our program\".<ref>Stites R. Revolutionary Dreams: Utopian Vision and Experimental Life in the Russian Revolution. Oxford: Oxford University Press. 1989. {{ISBN|0195055373}}; {{ISBN|978-0195055375}}./ p. 106</ref> He died in Moscow, and is buried in the [[Novodevichy Cemetery]].<ref>[http://rosgenea.ru/?a=12&p=15&r=4&s=%CB%EE%E3%E8%ED%EE%E2 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]</ref><ref>[http://novodevichiynecropol.narod.ru/8_2_lines.htm \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430, \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0435\u043a\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c, 8 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a, 22 \u0440\u044f\u0434]</ref>\n\n==Work==\n* \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d. \u0411\u0435\u0437\u0431\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a - \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433 \u043c\u0443\u0436\u0438\u043a\u0430 / \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : \u0411\u0435\u0437\u0431\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a, 1925. - 12 \u0441.;\n* \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d. \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435. (\u0415\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043b\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u0433?) : \u041b\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f, \u0447\u0438\u0442. \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u044e\u0437\u043e\u0432 25 \u044f\u043d\u0432. 1925 \u0433. / \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d. \"\u0411\u0435\u0437\u0431\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430\", 1925. - 32 \u0441.;\n* \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d. \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430 \u043e \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435 / \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \