421\u043e\u044e\u0437\u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : [\u0431. \u0438.], 1933. - \u041e\u0431\u043b., 15 \u0441., \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u0442. \u043b., 1 \u0441. \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u043b.;\n* \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d. \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u044b \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 / \u0422\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0442 \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 ; \u0420\u0438\u0441. \u0414. \u041c\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0430. - \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 : \u0411\u0435\u0437\u0431\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430, 1925. - 64 \u0441. : \u0438\u043b.;\n* Bibel und wissenschaft / Von Anton Loginow ; Deutsch bearbeitet von Leo Sarne. - Moskau : Zentralverlag der volker der Sowjetunion, 1927 (\u043a\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. \u0438\u0437\u0434-\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420). - 55 \u0441.;\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [[Atheistic Dictionary]] / [http://\u0432\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0435.\u0440\u0444/\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439-\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c-2/ \u041b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447]\n\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:Christ myth theory proponents]]\n[[Category:Historians of Christianity]]\n[[Category:Soviet atheists]]\n[[Category:Soviet historians]]\n[[Category:Russian atheism activists]]\n[[Category:Russian historians of religion]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_Loginov"}
{"title_page": "Falling in love", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n[[File:Albert Schr\u00f6der Musikalische Unterhaltung 1885.jpg|thumb|250px|Albert Schr\u00f6der - ''Musikalische Unterhaltung'' (circa 1885).]]\n{{Love sidebar|types}}\n[[File:Leighton-God Speed!.jpg|thumb|''[[God Speed (painting)|God Speed]]'' by English artist [[Edmund Leighton]], 1900: depicting an armored [[knight]] <nowiki/>departing for war and leaving behind his lover]]\n'''Falling in love''' is the development of strong feelings of attachment and [[love]], usually towards another person.\n  \nThe term is metaphorical, emphasising that the process, like the physical act of falling, is sudden, uncontrollable and leaves the lover in a vulnerable state, similar to \"fall ill\" or \"fall into a trap\".\n\nIt may also reflect the importance of the lower brain centers in the process,<ref>[[Desmond Morris]], ''The Naked Ape Trilogy'' p. 387</ref> which can lead the rational, accounting brain to conclude (in [[John Cleese]]'s words) that \"this falling in love routine is very bizarre....It borders on the [[occult]]\".<ref>R. Skinner/J. Cleese, ''[[Families and how to survive them]]'' (1994) p. 13</ref>\n\n==Factors==\n\n===Mental===\n\"Factors known to contribute strongly to falling in love include proximity, similarity, reciprocity, and physical attractiveness\",<ref>R. Crooks/K. Baur, ''Our Sexuality'' (2010) p. 223</ref> while at the same time, the process involves a re-activation of old childhood patterns of attachment.<ref>Robert M. Gordon, ''An Expert Looks at Love, Intimacy and Personal Growth'' (2008) p. xiv-v</ref> Deep-set psychological parallels between two people may also underpin their pairing-bonding,<ref>Robin Skynner/John Cleese, ''Families and how to survive them'' (London 1994) p. 14</ref> which can thus border on mere [[Narcissism|narcissistic]] identification\".<ref name=\"auto\">Elizabeth Young-Bruehl, ''Where Do We Fall When We Fall in Love?'' (2003) p. 20</ref>\n\n[[Carl Jung|Jungians]] view the process of falling in love as one of projecting the [[Anima and animus|anima or animus]] onto the other person, with all the potential for misunderstanding that can involve.<ref>Carl Jung, ''Man and his Symbols'' (1964) p. 191</ref>\n\n===Chemical===\n[[File:Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard - The Stolen Kiss.jpg|thumbnail| | [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]]\u2014''[[The Stolen Kiss (Fragonard)|The Stolen Kiss]]'' (circa late 1780s).]]\nTwo chemical reactions associated with falling in love are increases in [[oxytocin]] and [[vasopressin]];<ref>S. Kuchinskas, ''The Chemistry of Connection'' (2009) p. 88-9</ref> and [[Elisabeth Young-Bruehl]] has suggested that \"when we fall in love we are falling into a stream of naturally occurring [[amphetamines]] running through the emotional centres of our very own brains\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> With regard to [[sociobiology]], it is stressed that [[mate selection]] ''cannot'' be left to the head alone<ref>Daniel Goleman, ''Emotional Intelligence'' (London 1996) p. 4</ref> and must require complex neurochemical support.<ref>R. Crooks/K. Baur, ''Our Sexuality'' (2010) p. 186</ref>\n\nCritics of such [[Neo-Darwinism]] point out that over-simplistic physical arguments obscure the way sexual [[passion (emotion)|passion]] often leads not to secure attachment but to attachments thwarted, as well as the sheer frightening difficulties of all falling in love.<ref>Elizabeth Young-Bruehl, ''Where Do We Fall When We Fall in Love?'' (2003) p. 5</ref>\n\nBiologist [[Jeremy Griffith]] suggests that people fall in love in order to abandon themselves to the dream of an ideal state (being one free of the [[human condition]]).{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n\"Sexual desire and love not only show differences but also recruit a striking common set of brain areas that mediate somatosensory integration, reward expectation, and social cognition\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cacioppo|first=Stephanie|last2=Bianchi\u2010Demicheli|first2=Francesco|last3=Frum|first3=Chris|last4=Pfaus|first4=James G.|last5=Lewis|first5=James W.|date=2012-04|title=The Common Neural Bases Between Sexual Desire and Love: A Multilevel Kernel Density fMRI Analysis|url=https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1743-6109.2012.02651.x|journal=The Journal of Sexual Medicine|volume=9|issue=4|pages=1048\u20131054|doi=10.1111/j.1743-6109.2012.02651.x|issn=1743-6095}}</ref> Neuroimaging studies show that love and sexual desire share common chemical reactions in the brain. Both love and lust show neural activation in regions such as the cortical area (eg., middle gyrus, superior temporal guys, temporo-parietal junction, and occipital-temporal cortices) and the subcortical brain areas (eg., striatum, thalamus, hippocampus, anterior cingulate cortex, and ventral segmental area).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Bolmont|first=Mylene|last2=Cacioppo|first2=John T.|last3=Cacioppo|first3=Stephanie|date=2014-09|title=Love Is in the Gaze: An Eye-Tracking Study of Love and Sexual Desire|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0956797614539706|journal=Psychological Science|language=en|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1748\u20131756|doi=10.1177/0956797614539706|issn=0956-7976|pmc=PMC4273641|pmid=25031302}}</ref> The cortical area of the brain is correlated with a persons self-representation, goals-directed actions, and body image while the sub.<ref name=\":0\" /> Neuroimaging can also show the difference between love and desire.<ref name=\":0\" /> Some brain regions that contribute to either love or lust are the anterior inusla, posterior insula, and the ventral striatum. <ref name=\":0\" /> The anterior insula activates factors that contribute to love such as integrative representations. Where as the posterior insula are involved with factors that contribute to desire such as current sensations, feelings, and responses. <ref name=\":0\" /> The ventral striatum however, becomes activated during pleasurable rewarding experiences such as sex or food.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n=== Gender Differences ===\nMany studies have show a positive linear correlation between romantic popularity and physical attractiveness for woman more than men. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Ambwani|first=Suman|last2=Strauss|first2=Jaine|date=2007-02-01|title=Love Thyself Before Loving Others? A Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis of Gender Differences in Body Image and Romantic Love|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s11199-006-9143-7|journal=Sex Roles|language=en|volume=56|issue=1-2|pages=13\u201321|doi=10.1007/s11199-006-9143-7|issn=0360-0025}}</ref> Studies have shown that men subconsciously seek slenderness and sexiness whereas women seek status, permanence, and affluence before they seek physical attractiveness.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Timing==\n[[Stendhal]] charted the timing of falling in love in terms of what he called crystallization\u2014a first period of crystallization (of some six weeks)<ref>Eric Berne, ''Transactional Analysis in Psychotherapy'' (1961) p. 245</ref> which often involves obsessive brooding and the [[Idealization and devaluation|idealisation]] of the other via a coating of desire;<ref>R. J. Sternberg/K. Weiss, ''A New Psychology of Love'' (2013) p. 125-8</ref> a period of doubt; and then a final crystallization of love.<ref>I. A. Mabergoj, ''Reality and Truth in Literature'' (2013) p. 174</ref>\n\nEmpirical studies suggest that men fall in love earlier than women and women are quicker to fall out of love than men.<ref>E. R. Smith/D. M. Mackie, ''Social Psychology'' (2007) p. 420</ref>\n\n==Spiritual value==\nWhile some consider falling in love to be the nearest approach to a spiritual experience possible for the non-religious,<ref>J. Bailey/J. V. Bailey, ''Slowing Down to the Speed of Love'' (2004) p. 50</ref> others say its loss of [[Personal boundaries|ego boundaries]] is merely a temporary phenomenon which has little to do with, or may even block, spiritual development.<ref>M. Scott Peck, ''The Road Less Travelled'' (London 1990) p. 94-5</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How to Win Your Ex Back \u2014 5 Steps To Get Them Back|url=https://myrelationshipscenter.com/how-to-win-your-ex-back/}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Attachment theory]]\n*[[Dating]]\n*[[Flirting]]\n*[[Limerence]]\n*[[Love at first sight]]\n*[[Love sick (anxiety disorder)|Love sickness]]\n*[[Puppy love]]\n*[[Romantic orientation]]\n*[[Transference]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Robert J Sternberg and Karen Sternberg, editors. ''The New Psychology of Love. ''Yale University Press, 2008.\n*[[Denis de Rougemont]], ''Love in the Western World.'' Pantheon Books, 1956.\n*[[Eric Fromm]], ''The Art of Loving'' (1956)\n*[[Francesco Alberoni]], ''Falling in Love'' (New York, Random House, 1983)\n*[[Roland Barthes]], ''A Lover's Discourse'' (1990) \n\n[[Category:Love]]\n[[Category:Romance]]\n\n[[it:Innamoramento]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n[[File:Albert Schr\u00f6der Musikalische Unterhaltung 1885.jpg|thumb|250px|Albert Schr\u00f6der - ''Musikalische Unterhaltung'' (circa 1885).]]\n{{Love sidebar|types}}\n[[File:Leighton-God Speed!.jpg|thumb|''[[God Speed (painting)|God Speed]]'' by English artist [[Edmund Leighton]], 1900: depicting an armored [[knight]] <nowiki/>departing for war and leaving behind his lover]]\n'''Falling in love''' is the development of strong feelings of attachment and [[love]], usually towards another person.\n  \nThe term is metaphorical, emphasising that the process, like the physical act of falling, is sudden, uncontrollable and leaves the lover in a vulnerable state, similar to \"fall ill\" or \"fall into a trap\".\n\nIt may also reflect the importance of the lower brain centers in the process,<ref>[[Desmond Morris]], ''The Naked Ape Trilogy'' p. 387</ref> which can lead the rational, accounting brain to conclude (in [[John Cleese]]'s words) that \"this falling in love routine is very bizarre....It borders on the [[occult]]\".<ref>R. Skinner/J. Cleese, ''[[Families and how to survive them]]'' (1994) p. 13</ref>\n\n==Factors==\n\n===Mental===\n\"Factors known to contribute strongly to falling in love include proximity, similarity, reciprocity, and physical attractiveness\",<ref>R. Crooks/K. Baur, ''Our Sexuality'' (2010) p. 223</ref> while at the same time, the process involves a re-activation of old childhood patterns of attachment.<ref>Robert M. Gordon, ''An Expert Looks at Love, Intimacy and Personal Growth'' (2008) p. xiv-v</ref> Deep-set psychological parallels between two people may also underpin their pairing-bonding,<ref>Robin Skynner/John Cleese, ''Families and how to survive them'' (London 1994) p. 14</ref> which can thus border on mere [[Narcissism|narcissistic]] identification\".<ref name=\"auto\">Elizabeth Young-Bruehl, ''Where Do We Fall When We Fall in Love?'' (2003) p. 20</ref>\n\n[[Carl Jung|Jungians]] view the process of falling in love as one of projecting the [[Anima and animus|anima or animus]] onto the other person, with all the potential for misunderstanding that can involve.<ref>Carl Jung, ''Man and his Symbols'' (1964) p. 191</ref>\n\n===Chemical===\n[[File:Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard - The Stolen Kiss.jpg|thumbnail| | [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]]\u2014''[[The Stolen Kiss (Fragonard)|The Stolen Kiss]]'' (circa late 1780s).]]\nTwo chemical reactions associated with falling in love are increases in [[oxytocin]] and [[vasopressin]];<ref>S. Kuchinskas, ''The Chemistry of Connection'' (2009) p. 88-9</ref> and [[Elisabeth Young-Bruehl]] has suggested that \"when we fall in love we are falling into a stream of naturally occurring [[amphetamines]] running through the emotional centres of our very own brains\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> With regard to [[sociobiology]], it is stressed that [[mate selection]] ''cannot'' be left to the head alone<ref>Daniel Goleman, ''Emotional Intelligence'' (London 1996) p. 4</ref> and must require complex neurochemical support.<ref>R. Crooks/K. Baur, ''Our Sexuality'' (2010) p. 186</ref>\n\nCritics of such [[Neo-Darwinism]] point out that over-simplistic physical arguments obscure the way sexual [[passion (emotion)|passion]] often leads not to secure attachment but to attachments thwarted, as well as the sheer frightening difficulties of all falling in love.<ref>Elizabeth Young-Bruehl, ''Where Do We Fall When We Fall in Love?'' (2003) p. 5</ref>\n\nBiologist [[Jeremy Griffith]] suggests that people fall in love in order to abandon themselves to the dream of an ideal state (being one free of the [[human condition]]).{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n==Timing==\n[[Stendhal]] charted the timing of falling in love in terms of what he called crystallization\u2014a first period of crystallization (of some six weeks)<ref>Eric Berne, ''Transactional Analysis in Psychotherapy'' (1961) p. 245</ref> which often involves obsessive brooding and the [[Idealization and devaluation|idealisation]] of the other via a coating of desire;<ref>R. J. Sternberg/K. Weiss, ''A New Psychology of Love'' (2013) p. 125-8</ref> a period of doubt; and then a final crystallization of love.<ref>I. A. Mabergoj, ''Reality and Truth in Literature'' (2013) p. 174</ref>\n\nEmpirical studies suggest that men fall in love earlier than women and women are quicker to fall out of love than men.<ref>E. R. Smith/D. M. Mackie, ''Social Psychology'' (2007) p. 420</ref>\n\n==Spiritual value==\nWhile some consider falling in love to be the nearest approach to a spiritual experience possible for the non-religious,<ref>J. Bailey/J. V. Bailey, ''Slowing Down to the Speed of Love'' (2004) p. 50</ref> others say its loss of [[Personal boundaries|ego boundaries]] is merely a temporary phenomenon which has little to do with, or may even block, spiritual development.<ref>M. Scott Peck, ''The Road Less Travelled'' (London 1990) p. 94-5</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How to Win Your Ex Back \u2014 5 Steps To Get Them Back|url=https://myrelationshipscenter.com/how-to-win-your-ex-back/}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Attachment theory]]\n*[[Dating]]\n*[[Flirting]]\n*[[Limerence]]\n*[[Love at first sight]]\n*[[Love sick (anxiety disorder)|Love sickness]]\n*[[Puppy love]]\n*[[Romantic orientation]]\n*[[Transference]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Robert J Sternberg and Karen Sternberg, editors. ''The New Psychology of Love. ''Yale University Press, 2008.\n*[[Denis de Rougemont]], ''Love in the Western World.'' Pantheon Books, 1956.\n*[[Eric Fromm]], ''The Art of Loving'' (1956)\n*[[Francesco Alberoni]], ''Falling in Love'' (New York, Random House, 1983)\n*[[Roland Barthes]], ''A Lover's Discourse'' (1990) \n\n[[Category:Love]]\n[[Category:Romance]]\n\n[[it:Innamoramento]]\n", "name_user": "Katelynn.parker", "label": "safe", "comment": "copied from my sandbox : Katelynn.parker/sandbox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falling_in_love"}
{"title_page": "Urban Hymns", "text_new": "{{redirect|Neon Wilderness|the 1947 collection by Nelson Algren|The Neon Wilderness|the punk band|DC-Jam Records}}\n{{redirect|Velvet Morning|the song \"Velvet Mornings\" by Demis Roussos|Velvet Mornings}}\n{{redirect|Weeping Willow (song)|the ragtime piano composition by Scott Joplin|Weeping Willow (rag)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Urban Hymns\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Verve]]\n| cover      = The_Verve,_Urban_Hymns.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start_date|1997|9|29|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = October 1996 \u2013 May 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Olympic Studios]], London\n| genre      = [[Britpop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/the-10-best-britpop-albums-of-all-time-or-at-least-since-1993-or-so-6633707|title=The 10 Best Britpop Albums of All Time (or At Least Since 1993 or So)|work=The Village Voice|publisher=Suzan Gursoy|author=Laws, Mike|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 75:57\n| label      = [[Hut Records|Hut]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* The Verve\n* [[Chris Potter (producer)|Chris Potter]]\n* [[Martin Glover|Youth]] }}\n| prev_title = [[Five by Five (The Verve EP)|Five by Five]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[This Is Music: The Singles 92\u201398]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Urban Hymns\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Bitter Sweet Symphony]]\n | single1date = {{Start_date|1997|6|16|df=yes}}\n | single2     = [[The Drugs Don't Work]]\n | single2date = {{Start_date|1997|9|1|df=yes}}\n | single3     = [[Lucky Man (The Verve song)|Lucky Man]]\n | single3date = {{Start_date|1997|11|24|df=yes}}\n | single4     = [[Sonnet (The Verve song)|Sonnet]]\n | single4date = {{Start_date|1998|3|2|df=yes}}\n}}\n}}\n'''''Urban Hymns''''' is the third studio album by English [[alternative rock]] band [[the Verve]], released on 29 September 1997 on [[Hut Records]]. It earned nearly unanimous critical praise upon its release, and went on to become the band's best-selling release and one of the biggest selling albums of the year. {{As of|2019}}, ''Urban Hymns'' is  ranked the 18th [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling album]] in UK chart history<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-best-selling-albums-of-all-time-on-the-official-uk-chart__15551/|title=The best-selling albums of all time on the Official UK Chart |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> and has sold over ten million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/assets/files/top%2040%20albums.pdf|title=Top 40 Best Selling Albums: 28 July 1956&nbsp;\u2013 14 June 2009|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>\n\nThe album features the hit singles \"[[Bitter Sweet Symphony]]\", \"[[Lucky Man (The Verve song)|Lucky Man]]\" and UK number one \"[[The Drugs Don't Work]]\". The critical and commercial success of the album saw the band win two [[Brit Awards]] in 1998, including Best British Group, and appear on the cover of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine in April 1998.<ref name=\"The Brit Awards: The Verve\">[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/the-verve The Brit Awards: The Verve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202085636/http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/the-verve |date=2 February 2012 }} Brits.co.uk. Retrieved 11 February 2012</ref><ref name=\"Cover\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/1998-rolling-stone-covers-20040512/rs784-verve-76576240 1998 Rolling Stone Covers] Rolling Stone. Retrieved 11 February 2012</ref> \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song]].<ref name=\"41st Grammy Awards - 1999\">[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1999/grammys.htm 41st Grammy Awards \u2013 1999] Rock on the Net. Retrieved 12 February 2012</ref> It was also among ten albums nominated for the best British album of the previous 30 years by the [[Brit Awards]] in 2010, ultimately losing to ''[[(What's the Story) Morning Glory?]]'' by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]].<ref name=\"nme wilkinson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/brit-awards-2009-10-1303518|title=Liam Gallagher snubs Noel as Oasis win Brit Album Of 30 Years award|website=[[NME]]|first=Matt|last=Wilkinson|date=16 February 2010|accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Verve had previously released two albums, ''[[A Storm in Heaven]]'' in 1993 and ''[[A Northern Soul]]'' in 1995. The band had only achieved moderate commercial success up to that point, and the band split shortly after their second album due to internal conflicts. Vocalist [[Richard Ashcroft]] quickly reformed the group, with [[Simon Tong]], an old friend of the band on guitar, however Ashcroft realised [[Nick McCabe]]'s unique guitar style was required to complete the true Verve unit and later asked him to return. Tong also remained adding more guitar and keyboard/organ textures, making them a five-piece band and expanding their sound.<ref name=\"YELLOW\">[http://www.musicsaves.org/verve/interviews/36.shtml Follow the Yellow Brick Road]</ref>\n\nThe four-piece had already recorded several tracks for the album with [[Martin Glover|Youth]] as producer, but once McCabe returned they re-recorded several tracks and changed producers to [[Chris Potter (producer)|Chris Potter]]. McCabe said that in the next seven months of work, \"...&nbsp;the key tracks were recorded from scratch, but some of them were already there.\"<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.excellentonline.com/story/nick-mccabe-interview-733|title=Nick McCabe Interview|website=Excellent Online|access-date=30 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710211338/http://www.excellentonline.com/story/nick-mccabe-interview-733|archive-date=10 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe cover photo was taken in [[Richmond Park]], London by photographer Brian Cannon, who was also responsible for the artwork of the band's previous two albums. Cannon said that the simplicity of the image was because Ashcroft simply wanted fans to \"listen to the fucking record\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/the-verve/urban-hymns-album-facts-things-may-not-know/|title=Things You May Not Know About The Verve\u2019s Urban Hymns...|date=17 December 2018|website=Radio X|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe Verve were known for their music's complex, immersive sonic textures. \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" was a hit on both sides of the Atlantic, and remains the band's most well-known song. \"The Drugs Don't Work\", the band's only number one single in the [[UK]], became a concert staple for [[jam band]]s and other groups.{{Citation needed|reason=Which bands, specifically?|date=August 2017}}\n\nThe rest of the album alternated between wistful ballads like \"Sonnet\" and \"Space and Time\" (written by Richard Ashcroft), spacey grooves like \"Catching the Butterfly\" and \"The Rolling People\", all-out rockers like the pounding \"Come On\" (which existed in demo from the \"Northern Soul\" era) and psychedelic driven songs like \"Neon Wilderness\". The hidden track \"Deep Freeze\" features distorted guitars and a baby's cry sound. It has strong ambient influences that set it apart from the rest of the tracks in terms of composition and overall mood.\n\n==Release and reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=AMreview>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/urban-hymns-mw0000027235 |title=Urban Hymns \u2013 The Verve |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=1 March 2016 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = B+<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1997/10/10/music-review-urban-hymns |title=Urban Hymns |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=10 October 1997 |accessdate=1 March 2016 |last=Lanham |first=Tom}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Grave new world |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 September 1997 |last=Sullivan |first=Caroline}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/oct/12/entertainment/ca-41847 |title=The Verve 'Urban Hymns' Virgin  |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=12 October 1997 |accessdate=1 March 2016 |last=Scribner |first=Sara}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 8/10<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000202reviews.html |title=The Verve \u2013 Urban Hymns |work=[[NME]] |date=27 September 1997 |accessdate=1 March 2016 |last=Kessler |first=Ted |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817131041/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000202reviews.html |archivedate=17 August 2000}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 8.6/10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-verve-urban-hymns/ |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 September 2017 |accessdate=17 December 2017 |last=Berman |first=Stuart}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Songs of Praise |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=377 |date=October 2017 |last=Harris |first=John |authorlink=John Harris (critic) |page=112}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/theverve/albums/album/115189/review/5943294/urban_hymns |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns / Built to Spill: Perfect from Now On |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=25 December 1997 \u2013 8 January 1998 |accessdate=1 March 2016 |last=Fricke |first=David |authorlink=David Fricke |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202123030/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/theverve/albums/album/115189/review/5943294/urban_hymns |archivedate=2 December 2007}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RSGuide\">{{cite book |chapter=The Verve |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/849 849\u201350]}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev10Score = 5/5<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Shining Path |work=[[Select (magazine)|Select]] |issue=93 |date=March 1998 |last1=Aston |first1=Martin |last2=Harris |first2=John |authorlink2=John Harris (critic) |last3=Perry |first3=Andy |pages=76\u201377}}</ref>\n}}<!--List Automatically Moved by DASHBot-->\n''Urban Hymns'' received widespread critical praise upon its release.<ref name=\"Woodward\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/apr/29/willwoodward |title=Bittersweet success as the Verve split |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 April 1999 |accessdate=20 January 2017 |last=Woodward |first=Will}}</ref> ''[[Melody Maker]]'' hailed it as \"an album of unparalleled beauty so intent on grabbing at the strands of music's multi-hued history\".<ref name=\"Melody Maker Review\">{{cite journal |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns, Hut Records |work=[[Melody Maker]] |date=4 October 1997 |first=Martin |last=James |page=51}}</ref> Ted Kessler of ''[[NME]]'' praised ''Urban Hymns'' as the band's best album to date, adding that its first five songs alone \"pound all other guitar albums this year \u2013 bar [[Radiohead]]'s ''[[OK Computer]]'' \u2013 into the ground with their emotional ferocity and deftness of melodic touch.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/> Similarly, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critic [[David Fricke]] deemed it \"a defiantly psychedelic record \u2014 soaked in slipstream guitars and breezy strings, cruising at narcotic-shuffle velocity \u2014 about coping and crashing\".<ref name=\"RS\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Sara Scribner noted its \"lush, intricate, ethereal sound\" and felt that The Verve had \"delivered an achingly beautiful record that's just desperate enough to never get boring.\"<ref name=\"LAT\"/>\n\nIn a more mixed assessment, [[Greg Kot]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' felt that ''Urban Hymns'' was lacking in enough songs as memorable as \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" and \"The Drugs Don't Work\" to justify the album's long length.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-12-26/entertainment/9712260205_1_urban-hymns-richard-ashcroft-moment |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=26 December 1997 |accessdate=1 January 2017 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' cited the latter track as a \"choice cut\",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=10712 |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns |publisher=RobertChristgau.com |accessdate=1 January 2017 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref> indicating a good song on \"an album that isn't worth your time or money.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg90/grades-90s.php |title=CG 90s: Key to Icons |publisher=RobertChristgau.com |accessdate=1 January 2017 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n\n''Urban Hymns'' spent 12 weeks at the top of the [[UK Albums Chart]], with a total of 124 weeks on the chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/verve |title=Verve |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> It also became The Verve's first charting album in the United States, where it debuted at number 63 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref>Author unknown. [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5926044/bridge_to_the_past \"Bridge to the Past\"]. ''Rolling Stone''. 8 October 1997.</ref> giving the band their first commercial success in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/151567/the-verve-take-massive-attack-to-american-shores/ |title=The Verve Take Massive Attack To American Shores |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=20 April 1998 |accessdate=20 January 2017 |last=Devenish |first=Colin}}</ref> ''Urban Hymns'' ultimately peaked at number 23 on the chart and was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] on 4 April 1998;<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite certification|region=United States|artist=Verve, The|title=Urban Hymns|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> it remains the group's best-selling album in the United States to date, with over 1.3 million copies sold {{as of|2009|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Ask Billboard\">Trust, Gary. [http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/thisday/ask-billboard-mariah-carey-abba-oasis-the-1003934063.story \"Ask Billboard: \"English Beat\"]. [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]. 23 January 2009.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''[[Melody Maker]]'' named ''Urban Hymns'' as the number one album of 1997 in its year-end list,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Albums of the Year 1997 |work=[[Melody Maker]] |volume=74 |issue=51 |date=20\u201327 December 1997 |pages=66\u201367 |issn=0025-9012}}</ref> and the album ranked at number three on ''[[NME]]''{{'}}s year-end critics' poll.<ref>{{cite journal |title=1997 Critics' Poll |work=[[NME]] |date=20\u201327 December 1997 |pages=78\u201379}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' also included it in their own list of the best albums of 1997,<ref>{{cite journal |title=50 Best Albums of 1997 |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=136 |date=January 1998 |page=115}}</ref> and it ranked at number 18 on ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s year-end [[Pazz & Jop]] critics' poll.<ref name=\"VV Albums 1997\">{{cite news |url=http://robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres97.php |title=The 1997 Pazz & Jop Critics Poll |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=24 February 1998 |accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> At the [[1998 Brit Awards]], ''Urban Hymns'' won the award for Best British Album and The Verve themselves were awarded Best British Group.<ref name=\"Woodward\"/> The same year, Richard Aschroft won an [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for Songwriter of the Year.<ref name=\"Woodward\"/> The album was also shortlisted for the [[Mercury Prize]], which was ultimately awarded to [[Gomez (band)|Gomez]]' ''[[Bring It On (Gomez album)|Bring It On]]''.<ref name=where>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/music/mercury+winners+where+are+they+now/605557 |title=Mercury winners: where are they now? |publisher=[[Channel 4]] |date=18 July 2007 |accessdate=10 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091008131117/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/music/mercury+winners+where+are+they+now/605557 |archivedate=8 October 2009}}</ref> By April 1999, however, renewed tensions within the band, particularly between Ashcroft and McCabe, would lead The Verve to split up for a second time, at the height of their critical and commercial success.<ref name=\"RSGuide\"/><ref name=\"Woodward\"/>\n\nIn the years following its release, ''Urban Hymns'' has received much acclaim. In 2000 it was voted number 213 in [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|author=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=104}}</ref> ''Q'' included it in their 1999 list of the 90 best albums of the 1990s,<ref>{{cite journal |title=90 Best Albums of the 1990s |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=159 |date=December 1999 |page=92}}</ref> while the magazine's readers voted it the eighteenth best album of all-time in 1998,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Q Readers' All Time Top 100 Albums |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=137 |date=February 1998}}</ref> later moved up to sixteenth place in a similar list compiled in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Q Readers' All Time Top 100 Albums |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=235 |date=February 2006}}</ref> The Verve were awarded with the first ever ''Q'' Classic Album award for ''Urban Hymns'' at the 2007 [[Q Awards|''Q'' Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7033815.stm |title=Winners in full: Q Awards 2007 |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 October 2007 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and the following year, ''Urban Hymns'' was ranked as the tenth best British album of all time in a poll jointly conducted by ''Q'' and [[HMV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7249473.stm |title=Oasis top best British album poll |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=18 February 2008 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> It was also nominated for Best British Album of the Last 30 Years at the [[2010 Brit Awards]], but lost to [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]' ''[[(What's the Story) Morning Glory?]]''.<ref>[http://www.brits.co.uk/brits-2010 BRIT Awards 2010 Homepage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218013515/http://www.brits.co.uk/brits-2010 |date=18 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn a retrospective review, [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] called ''Urban Hymns'' \"a rich album that revitalizes rock traditions without ever seeming less than contemporary\", further crediting it as the album that The Verve had \"been striving to make since their formation.\"<ref name=AMreview/> [[BBC Music]] critic Wendy Roby wrote in 2010 that ''Urban Hymns'' \"still sounds thrilling\" and \"soars with autumnal melancholy\", crediting the album's mix of \"massive, sweeping\" arrangements and Ashcroft's \"heartbreaking\" lyrics as its key characteristics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/vqvh/ |title=The Verve Urban Hymns Review |publisher=[[BBC Music]] |date=2010 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' wrote that \"the most striking qualities of ''Urban Hymns'' now are its musical coherence and the powerfully sustained mood of melancholic stoicism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1033202/a/urban+hymns.htm |title=The Verve: Urban Hymns |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |date= |accessdate=20 January 2017 |page=108}}</ref> On the other hand, Emily Tartanella of ''[[Magnet (magazine)|Magnet]]'' felt that ''Urban Hymns'' was undeserving of its accolades, calling it \"one of the most bloated, boring and overpraised albums of the '90s.\"<ref name=\"magnet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.magnetmagazine.com/2009/08/18/the-overunder-britpop/ |title=The Over/Under: Britpop |work=[[Magnet (magazine)|Magnet]] |date=18 August 2009 |accessdate=1 January 2017 |last=Tartanella |first=Emily}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Richard Ashcroft]], except where noted.\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = International version\n| extra_column = Producer<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://musicsaves.org/verve/discog/urban.shtml|title=Verve Discography|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"fan discography\">{{cite web|url=http://musicsaves.org/verve/discog/bss1.shtml|title=Verve Discography|publisher=}}</ref>\n| title1 = [[Bitter Sweet Symphony]]\n| note1 = \n| length1 = 5:58\n| writer1 = \n| extra1 = {{flatlist|\n* The Verve\n* [[Martin Glover|Youth]] }}\n| title2 = [[Sonnet (The Verve song)|Sonnet]]\n| note2 = \n| length2 = 4:21\n| writer2 = \n| extra2 = {{flatlist|\n* The Verve\n* Youth }}\n| title3 = The Rolling People\n| note3 = \n| length3 = 7:01\n| writer3 = The Verve\n| extra3 = {{flatlist|\n* The Verve\n* [[Chris Potter (producer)|Chris Potter]] }}\n| title4 = [[The Drugs Don't Work]]\n| note4 = \n| length4 = 5:05\n| writer4 = \n| extra4 = {{flatlist|\n* The Verve\n* Youth }}\n| title5 = Catching the Butterfly\n| length5 = 6:26\n| writer5 = The Verve\n| extra5 = {